<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">2</font></p>

<font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='2',FILE='C:\jms\jgronse\04-3778-1\task103431\3778-1-ba.htm',USER='jgronse',CD='Mar 30 09:05 2004' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">
</font>

<p align="center" style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;">&nbsp;</p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><a name="PartI"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">PART I</font></b></a></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item1Business"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM
1 - BUSINESS</font></b></a></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">General</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet Systems, Inc. is a
specialty air carrier for time-sensitive deliveries, operating between most
U.S. cities and delivering over 20,000 time-critical shipments each working day.&#160; AirNet is the leading transporter of
cancelled checks and related information for the U.S. banking industry, meeting
more than 2,500 daily deadlines.&#160; AirNet
also provides specialized, high-priority delivery services to customers,
primarily those involved in the medical, critical parts and entertainment
industries.&#160; AirNet also provides
passenger charter services through its wholly-owned subsidiary, Jetride, Inc.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet operates a fleet of
approximately 120 aircraft (including 33 Learjets and 15 Cessna Caravan
turboprops) that depart from over 100 cities and complete more than 420 flights
per night, primarily Monday through Thursday.&#160;&#160;
In addition, Jetride, Inc. operates nine Learjets that offer private
passenger charter services.&#160; To
supplement its air transportation network, AirNet uses commercial airlines
during daytime and weekend hours when its aircraft are operating under a
limited flight schedule.&#160; Approximately
70% of AirNet&#146;s shipments are carried on AirNet&#146;s own air transportation
network.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In addition to regularly
scheduled cargo services, AirNet offers on-demand cargo charter delivery
services 24 hours per day, seven days a week.&#160;
AirNet provides ground pick-up and delivery services throughout the
nation seven days per week, using a combination of company personnel and a
network of approximately 450 vendors and independent contractors.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s integrated air and
ground network provides dependable, time-critical delivery services to its
customers.&#160; Later pick-up and earlier
delivery times than those offered by other national carriers is one of the
primary differentiating characteristics of AirNet&#146;s time-critical delivery
network.&#160; AirNet&#146;s flight schedule is
designed to provide delivery times between midnight and 8:00 a.m., providing
earlier delivery times than those available through other national
carriers.&#160; AirNet uses a number of
proprietary customer service and management information systems to track, sort,
dispatch and control the flow of packages throughout AirNet&#146;s delivery
system.&#160; AirNet provides customer
service 24 hours per day, seven days a week to handle any inquiries,
discrepancies or supply requests, as well as to provide proof of delivery
documentation, all of which are value-added features of AirNet&#146;s service.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet Systems, Inc. was
incorporated as a C-corporation under the laws of the State of Ohio on
February&nbsp;15, 1996.&#160; AirNet&#146;s
principal executive offices are located at 3939&nbsp;International Gateway,
Columbus, Ohio 43219, and can be reached at (614) 237-9777.&#160; AirNet&#146;s Internet web site address is </font>www.airnet.com (this uniform resource
locator (URL) is an inactive textual reference only and is not intended to
incorporate AirNet&#146;s website into this Annual Report on Form 10-K).</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet makes available free of
charge on or through its website, its annual report on Form 10-K, quarterly
reports on Form 10-Q, current reports on Form 8-K, and amendments to those
reports filed or furnished pursuant to Section 13(a) or 15(d) of the Securities
Exchange Act of 1934, as amended (the &#147;Exchange Act&#148;), as soon as reasonably
practicable after AirNet electronically files such material with, or furnishes
it to, the Securities and Exchange Commission (the &#147;SEC&#148;).</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Delivery Services</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Bank services</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Bank services,
which generate approximately 69% of AirNet&#146;s revenues, primarily consist of
cancelled check delivery.&#160; AirNet&#146;s
time-critical cancelled check delivery service allows its banking customers to
reduce their float costs and related processing fees.&#160; AirNet also transports items, such as proof of delivery reports
and interoffice mail, for many of the same bank customers.&#160; AirNet has historically priced its Bank
services based on the tier of service, and by the pound, on a
customer-by-customer basis.&#160; The U.S.
banking industry, including commercial banks, savings banks and Federal Reserve
banks, represents AirNet&#146;s largest category of customers. AirNet&#146;s bank
customers represent over 100 of the nation&#146;s largest bank holding companies.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Express services</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Express
services, which generate approximately 25% of AirNet&#146;s revenues, focus on
customers with time-critical delivery needs.&#160;
Express services are primarily targeted at customers involved in the
medical, critical parts and entertainment industries.&#160; In the medical industry, Express services are offered to
customers shipping packages that require specialized handling, the
transportation of which is often highly regulated by varying governmental
authorities.&#160; Targeted markets within
the medical industry include producers and recipients of radioactive pharmaceuticals,
diagnostic specimens, blood, umbilical cord blood, human tissue and organs.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Express
services are also marketed to customers whose shipment needs are highly time
sensitive or time definite, including just-in-time manufacturers, critical
parts suppliers and customers involved in the media and entertainment
industries.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">3</font></p>


<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='3',FILE='C:\jms\jgronse\04-3778-1\task103431\3778-1-ba.htm',USER='jgronse',CD='Mar 30 09:05 2004' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">
</font>

<p align="center" style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;">&nbsp;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">For those
customers requiring time-critical delivery options not available on AirNet&#146;s
regularly scheduled routes, on-demand cargo charter services are available 24
hours per day, seven days a week.&#160;
On-demand charters may be scheduled in advance or on an as-needed basis.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Passenger Charter Services</font></i></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Jetride, Inc., a wholly-owned
subsidiary of AirNet, provides private passenger charter services that offer
customers a safe, fast, and convenient way to travel.&#160; Jetride&#146;s private passenger charter service is available 24 hours
a day, 7 days a week primarily within the continental United States and
neighboring countries.&#160;&#160; Jetride provides
charter services arranged through third-party charter brokers and, to a lesser
extent, to retail customers.&#160; Jetride
operates its nine passenger Learjets from various locations across the country.&#160; All passenger Learjets have been configured
to comfortably carry seven or eight passengers.&#160; All passenger charter pilots are Airline Transport Pilot rated &#150;
the highest </font>Federal
Aviation Administration (&#147;FAA&#148;) rating possible.&#160; Jetride, Inc. is certified by both the Wyvern Network
of Charter Operators and the Aviation Research Group/US, industry leaders in
aviation rating.&#160; Jetride anticipates adding additional
Learjets to its passenger fleet during 2004 as it continues to expand its
passenger charter services.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Aviation Services</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet operates a fixed base operation
from AirNet&#146;s Columbus, Ohio facility, offering retail aviation fuel sales and
related ground support services.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Business Strategy</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet believes that its Bank
services revenue will decline in future periods as a result of the continuing
evolution of electronic alternatives to the physical movement of cancelled
checks.&#160;&#160; In October 2003, the Check 21 Act was signed into law.&#160; When it becomes effective in October of
2004, the Check 21 Act will require that
all financial institutions accept either the physical cancelled check, or an
image replacement document in lieu of a physical cancelled check.&#160; AirNet believes that this may accelerate the
transition in the banking industry to the electronic clearing of cancelled
checks.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In response to these changes in
the banking industry, AirNet has been pursuing a multi-year strategy to
transition and diversify AirNet by pursuing growth opportunities for its
Express and Passenger Charter services.&#160;
During this transition period, AirNet continues to respond to the
changing needs of its bank customers.&#160;
AirNet intends to focus on expanding its Express services to customers
in time-critical markets, and time-definite delivery markets, such as medical,
radioactive pharmaceutical, on-demand cargo charters and those that benefit
most from just-in-time inventories.&#160;
AirNet&#146;s air transportation network offers customers in these industries
competitive advantages through delivery speed, customer service, and custody
and control throughout the delivery service.&#160;
AirNet believes its flexible and reliable air transportation network and
demonstrated expertise in providing time-critical deliveries to the banking
industry for over 29 years positions it to provide these services to the
Express market.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet is also adapting to changes
in the banking industry by reconfiguring its operational structure and
associated costs to align with the expected volume and revenue changes.&#160; AirNet continues to refine its pricing model
for bank customers by introducing pricing models that contain both fixed fee
and volume-based components.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet continues to invest in
additional aircraft to expand its passenger charter operations.&#160; AirNet believes that demand for private
charter services will continue to grow as commercial airlines continue to
tighten schedules and require longer boarding times due to security concerns.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The diversification of AirNet&#146;s
business will likely require significant changes in its air transportation
network, a greater investment in sales and marketing during the transition, and
investment in additional service capabilities and technologies to serve a more
diverse customer group.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Fast Forward Solutions</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Fast Forward Solutions,
LLC, a wholly-owned subsidiary of AirNet, was formed to explore growth
opportunities associated with existing and emerging image replacement platforms
and technologies. </font>Fast Forward Solutions and NetDeposit, Inc., a
developer of electronic check processing technologies, have signed a term sheet
regarding their intent to finalize an agreement to provide a standard image
replacement document check processing solution to the banking industry.&#160; While negotiations with NetDeposit, Inc. are
continuing as of March 30, 2004, no agreement had been entered into between
Fast Forward Solutions and NetDeposit, Inc. and there can be no assurances that
such an agreement will be finalized.</p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">4</font></p>


<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='4',FILE='C:\jms\jgronse\04-3778-1\task103431\3778-1-ba.htm',USER='jgronse',CD='Mar 30 09:05 2004' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">
</font>

<p align="center" style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;">&nbsp;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Operations</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Air operations</font></i></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s air operations are
headquartered in Columbus, Ohio.&#160; AirNet
utilizes an extensive screening process to evaluate potential pilots prior to
hiring. These pilots meet stringent company qualifications, as well as all
required FAA requirements.&#160; All new
pilots must satisfactorily complete a five-week training program conducted by
AirNet&#146;s flight training staff prior to assignment of pilot duties.&#160; This training program includes flight
simulator training prior to any actual flight time in an aircraft, as well as
intensive ground instruction.&#160; </font>Additionally, new pilots gain operating experience in a structured&nbsp;setting
prior to assignment in order to gain a familiarity with AirNet&#146;s route system
and the unique demands of&nbsp;the flight environment.&#160; In addition
to FAA requirements, pilots providing Passenger Charter services for Jetride,
Inc. must also meet additional in-flight experience requirements specifically
related to the types of Learjets operated by Jetride.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s central dispatch
system ties together all components of the air operation. Departure and arrival
times are continuously updated, and weather conditions throughout the nation
are constantly monitored. AirNet dispatchers remain in constant contact with
pilots, out-based hub managers, fuelers, maintenance technicians and ground
delivery personnel to identify and minimize any potential delays in the
delivery process.&#160; AirNet also uses
commercial airlines, primarily to transport shipments during the daytime and
weekend hours when its aircraft are operating under a limited flight schedule.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Capacity management is an
important factor in achieving profitable growth of AirNet&#146;s package delivery
services.&#160; AirNet&#146;s air transportation
network is positioned around a flexible national route structure designed to
facilitate late pick-up and early delivery times, minimize delays and simplify
flight scheduling.&#160; AirNet&#146;s flexible
route structure allows it to respond to the changing volume needs of its
customers or to take advantage of emerging opportunities in its Express
services business.&#160; AirNet&#146;s primary hub
in Columbus, Ohio, and several mini-hubs across the nation, are located
primarily in less congested regional airports. These locations, in conjunction
with AirNet&#146;s off-peak departure and arrival times, provide easy take-off and
landings, convenient loading and unloading, and fast refueling and maintenance.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet employs approximately 80
aircraft and avionics technicians in eight separate locations across the
country performing all levels of maintenance on AirNet&#146;s fleet of
aircraft.&#160; AirNet has an in-house engine
shop at the Columbus facility where some of the piston engines are overhauled
on-site, thereby reducing aircraft downtime and controlling costs.&#160; AirNet also performs avionics
troubleshooting and repair at the Columbus facility to provide for maximum
efficiency and minimum aircraft downtime for the fleet.&#160; AirNet&#146;s aircraft maintenance center at its
Columbus hub recently received ISO 9001:2000 certification.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Shipment&#160;
processing</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Bank shipments are pre-sorted
by bank personnel and packaged in AirNet-supplied bags color-coded to easily
identify the final destination.&#160; Express
shipments are packaged in either AirNet-provided packaging or the customers&#146;
packaging.&#160; Shipments transported on
AirNet&#146;s air transportation network are typically picked up by a courier and
transported to the local airport where the airbill is either scanned using bar
code technology or entered manually.&#160;
Information on each airbill pertaining to the shipper, receiver, airbill
number and applicable deadline is captured and downloaded into AirNet&#146;s
computer system, where it is available to AirNet&#146;s customer service
representatives (&#147;CSRs&#148;).&#160; Upon arrival
at AirNet&#146;s Columbus hub or one of its mini-hubs, the shipment is off-loaded,
sorted by destination and reloaded onto an aircraft.&#160; At the destination city, the shipment is off-loaded for the final
time and delivered by courier to the receiver.&#160;
When delivered, information from the airbill is once again captured and
downloaded into AirNet&#146;s computer system. Delivery information for all
shipments is then available on-line to the customers and AirNet&#146;s CSRs.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">For
banking customers meeting daytime banking deadlines and Express</font>
customers requiring next-flight-out timing, shipments are typically picked up
by a courier and transported via commercial airlines or other integrators to
destination cities where couriers accept the packages and deliver them to their
final destinations.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Ground support</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet manages its ground
delivery services through the combined use of employees and a network of
approximately 450 independent contractors and vendor couriers.&#160; Independent contractors and vendors perform
the majority of ground delivery services, allowing AirNet to better match its
ground costs with its volume requirements.&#160;
In some situations, employees are used for ground delivery services on
scheduled routes where volume requirements economically justify employing
full-time couriers.&#160; Dispatching
functions related to ground delivery services occur at both the Columbus, Ohio
hub and on a regional basis in some of the major cities served.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Mercury Business Services</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On August 11, 2003,
AirNet sold the assets of its Mercury Business Services division to Mercury
Business Services, Inc., a Delaware corporation owned by a group that includes
the original owners of the Mercury business.&#160;
AirNet had acquired Mercury Business Services in August of 1998.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">5</font></p>


<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='5',FILE='C:\jms\jgronse\04-3778-1\task103431\3778-1-ba.htm',USER='jgronse',CD='Mar 30 09:05 2004' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">
</font>

<p align="center" style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;">&nbsp;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Regulation</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet holds an air carrier
certificate granted by </font>the FAA pursuant to Part 135 of the Federal Aviation Regulations.
In addition, Jetride, Inc. holds its own air carrier certificate granted by the
FAA pursuant to Part 135.&#160; These
certificates are of unlimited duration and remain in effect so long as AirNet
and Jetride maintain their standards of safety and meet the operational
requirements of the Federal Aviation Regulations.&#160; The FAA&#146;s regulatory authority relates primarily to operational
aspects of air transportation, including aircraft standards and maintenance,
personnel, and ground facilities.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
U. S. Department of Transportation (&#147;DOT&#148;) and Transportation Security
Administration (&#147;TSA&#148;) have regulatory authority concerning operational and
security concerns in transportation, respectively, including safety, insurance
and hazardous materials.&#160; AirNet holds
various operational certificates issued by these agencies, including party
status to DOT E-7060, which permits AirNet to transport higher volumes of
time-critical radioactive pharmaceuticals than is allowed by the DOT for most
carriers.&#160; Party status to DOT E-7060 is
renewed every two years, with AirNet&#146;s renewal due November 2004.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet
is also subject to Food and Drug Administration regulation of its
transportation of pharmaceuticals.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In
addition to federal regulations, AirNet&#146;s operations are subject to various
state and local regulations, and in many instances, require permits and
licenses from state authorities.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet
believes that both AirNet and Jetride have all permits, approvals and licenses
required to conduct their respective operations and that they are&#160; in compliance with applicable regulatory
requirements relating to their operations including</font> all
applicable noise level regulations.&#160;
Current noise level regulations require that AirNet modify its 3 Model
25 Learjets prior to the end of 2004. AirNet intends to retire the Learjet 25&#146;s
prior to the end of 2004.&#160; AirNet is
working proactively with various local governments to minimize noise issues;
however, future noise pollution regulations could require the modification or
replacement of other AirNet aircraft.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Seasonality</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">See
&#147;Item 7:&#160; Management&#146;s Discussion and
Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations&#148; under the heading
&#147;Seasonality and Variability in Quarterly Results&#148; of this Annual Report on
Form 10-K for a discussion of the seasonal aspects of AirNet&#146;s business.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Competition</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The air and ground courier
industry is highly competitive.&#160;
AirNet&#146;s primary competitor in the transportation of cancelled checks is
the Federal Reserve&#146;s Check Relay Network. The actions of the Federal Reserve
are regulated by the Monetary Control Act, which requires the Federal Reserve
to price its services at actual cost plus a set percentage private sector
adjustment factor. AirNet believes that the purpose of the Monetary Control Act
is to curtail the possibility of predatory pricing by the Federal Reserve when
it competes with the private sector. No assurance beyond the remedies of law
can be given that the Federal Reserve will comply with the Monetary Control
Act.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In the private sector, there
are a large number of smaller, regional carriers that transport cancelled
checks, none of which AirNet believes have significant interstate market share.
The two largest private sector air couriers, FedEx and United Parcel Service
(&#147;UPS&#148;), both carry cancelled checks where the deadlines being pursued fit into
their existing system.&#160; AirNet does not
believe that FedEx or UPS represent significant competitors in the
time-critical cancelled check market to date.&#160;
AirNet provides customized service for its customer base, often with
later pick-ups and earlier deliveries than the large, national couriers
provide.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet competes with commercial
airlines and numerous other carriers in its Express delivery business.&#160; AirNet estimates its market share in this
industry at less than 1%.&#160; AirNet
believes that this market represents a significant expansion opportunity for
ultra time-critical shipments requiring later pick-ups or earlier deliveries
than are typically provided by major integrators and freight forwarders.&#160; AirNet believes that it is in an excellent
position to leverage the use of its national air network system, AirNet&#146;s
proprietary information technology and its historically high on-time
performance level to compete in this market.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In the passenger charter
business, AirNet competes with other owner/operators and charter brokers of
small business jets.&#160; AirNet believes
its nationwide network of maintenance and related support facilities provides
added flexibility in deploying and servicing the passenger charter aircraft
fleet to meet customer demands.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Environmental matters</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet intends to commence construction of a
new corporate and operational headquarters on land leased from the Columbus
Regional Port Authority in 2004.&#160;
Portions of the leased land, as well as portions of the aircraft ramp,
on which AirNet intends to conduct a significant portion of its Columbus
operations, contain known pollution conditions.&#160; The </font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">6</font></p>


<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='6',FILE='C:\jms\jgronse\04-3778-1\task103431\3778-1-ba.htm',USER='jgronse',CD='Mar 30 09:05 2004' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">
</font>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">appropriate amended post closure plan and no
further action letters addressing these sites are to be supplied to AirNet by
the Columbus Regional Port Authority prior to beginning construction.&#160; AirNet has received the applicable no
further action letters.&#160; Identification
of additional pollution conditions on the leased land or attached ramp or the
inability of the Columbus Regional Port Authority to provide the approved
amended post closure plan could increase costs and have an adverse affect on
AirNet&#146;s ability to construct the Rickenbacker facility.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet believes that compliance
with applicable laws and regulations governing environmental matters have not
had, and are not expected to have, a material effect on AirNet&#146;s capital
expenditures, operations or competitive position.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Employees</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">As of December 31, 2003, AirNet
employed 895 persons, which includes approximately 225 pilots.&#160; AirNet&#146;s employees are not represented by
any union or covered by any collective bargaining agreement.&#160; AirNet has experienced no work stoppages and
believes that its relationship with employees is good.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item2Properties"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM
2 - PROPERTIES</font></b></a></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Operating facilities</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet owns its corporate and
operational headquarters at 3939 International Gateway in Columbus, Ohio (the
&#147;Port Columbus Facility&#148;).&#160; The Port
Columbus Facility has 80,000 square feet and sits on land owned by the Columbus
Regional Airport Authority (the &#147;Authority&#148;).&#160;
AirNet has a 25-year land lease with the Authority, which expires on
December 31, 2009 and contains a 20-year renewal option.&#160; AirNet&#146;s headquarters is currently used for
operations, training, aircraft maintenance, vehicle maintenance and general and
administrative functions.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet leases additional space
at 555 Morrison Avenue in Gahanna, Ohio.&#160;
The space is used for administrative support personnel.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On January 20, 2004, AirNet entered
into a Land Lease with the Authority to lease approximately 8 acres located
within the Rickenbacker International Airport (&#147;Rickenbacker&#148;).&#160; Rickenbacker is located in Franklin and
Pickaway Counties, Ohio, southeast of Columbus, Ohio, approximately fifteen
miles from its current Port Columbus Facility.&#160;
AirNet intends to construct a new corporate and operational headquarters
at the Rickenbacker site (the &#147;Rickenbacker Facility&#148;).&#160; Construction of the Rickenbacker Facility is
anticipated to be completed in the summer of 2005. Upon completion of the
Rickenbacker Facility, AirNet&#146;s current corporate and operational functions
that are conducted at the Port Columbus Facility, and the administrative
functions being conducted at 555 Morrison Avenue, will be consolidated at the
new Rickenbacker Facility.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In anticipation of the AirNet&#146;s
move to its new Rickenbacker Facility, on January 20, 2004, AirNet entered into
an agreement to sell its Port Columbus Facility to the Authority for
$3,850,000.&#160; AirNet has retained the
right to continue to occupy the Port Columbus Facility until construction and
relocation to the new Rickenbacker Facility is complete.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet operates at
approximately 40 additional locations throughout the country. These locations,
which are leased from unrelated third parties, generally include office space
and/or a section of the lessor&#146;s hangar or ramp.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Fleet</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Cargo aircraft</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">7</font></p>


<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='7',FILE='C:\jms\jgronse\04-3778-1\task103431\3778-1-ba.htm',USER='jgronse',CD='Mar 30 09:05 2004' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">
</font>

<p align="center" style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;">&nbsp;</p>


<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="1" width="25%" noshade color="black" align="left">

</font></div>


<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(1)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Maximum
payload in pounds for a one-hour flight plus required fuel reserves.</p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(2)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Maximum
range in nautical miles, assuming zero wind, full fuel and maximum payload.</p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(3)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Maximum
speed in knots, assuming maximum payload</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">An inventory of spare engines
and parts is maintained for each aircraft type.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Learjet 35 is among the fastest, most reliable and most fuel-efficient small
jet aircraft available in the world and meets all Stage Three noise
requirements currently being implemented across the country.&#160; The Learjet 25 is a smaller jet aircraft
with slightly smaller payload and range capabilities.&#160; The Learjet 25 is not Stage Three compliant and will be phased
out of scheduled operations in 2004.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Cessna Caravan Super Cargomaster aircraft is a turbo-prop aircraft.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Piper Navajo, Beech Baron and Cessna 310 are twin-engine piston aircraft.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Passenger charter aircraft</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The following table shows
information about AirNet&#146;s passenger charter aircraft fleet as of December 31,
2003:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="90%" style="border-collapse:collapse;width:90.0%;">
 <tr>
  <td width="39%" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext .5pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:39.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Aircraft Type</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p align="center" style="font-size:1.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;">&nbsp;</p>
  </td>
  <td width="10%" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext .5pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:10.0%;">
  <p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Owned</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p align="center" style="font-size:1.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;">&nbsp;</p>
  </td>
  <td width="10%" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext .5pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:10.0%;">
  <p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Leased or<br>
  Managed</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p align="center" style="font-size:1.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;">&nbsp;</p>
  </td>
  <td width="10%" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext .5pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:10.0%;">
  <p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Seating
  (1)</font></b></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="1" width="25%" noshade color="black" align="left">

</font></div>


<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(1)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Maximum
number of passengers</p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(2)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Maximum
range in nautical miles, assuming zero wind, full fuel and full payload.</p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(3)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Maximum
speed in knots, assuming full payload</p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(4)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Includes
one model 35A and one model 60 aircraft operated under a management agreement</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">An inventory of parts is
maintained for each type of Learjet.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Learjet 60 is a midsize
business jet with transcontinental range and</font> meets all Stage Three noise requirements.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Vehicles</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet operates a fleet of
approximately 90 ground transportation vehicles.&#160;&#160; Vehicles range in size from passenger cars to full sized
vans.&#160; AirNet also rents lightweight
trucks for certain weekend ground routes.&#160;
In 2001, AirNet entered into a leasing agreement with a third party
provider and began replacing owned vehicles with leased vehicles, as
replacement became necessary.&#160; AirNet
leased 62 vehicles as of December 31, 2003.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item3LegalProceedings"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM
3 - LEGAL PROCEEDINGS</font></b></a></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">There are no pending legal
proceedings involving AirNet other than routine litigation incidental to its
business. In the opinion of AirNet&#146;s management, these proceedings should not,
individually or in the aggregate, have a material adverse effect on AirNet&#146;s
results of operations or financial condition.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item4SubmissionOfMattersToAVote"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM 4 - SUBMISSION OF MATTERS TO A VOTE OF
SECURITY HOLDERS</font></b></a></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">No matters were submitted to a
vote of security holders during the fourth quarter of 2003.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">8</font></p>


<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Joel E. Biggerstaff has served
as AirNet&#146;s Chairman of the Board since August 2001, Chief Executive Officer
since April 2000, and&#160; President since
August 1999.&#160; He also served as AirNet&#146;s
Chief Operating Officer from August 1999 to February 2004.&#160; He has also served as director of AirNet
since May 2000.&#160; Prior to joining
AirNet, Mr. Biggerstaff served as President of the Southern Region of Corporate
Express Delivery Systems, a national expedited distribution service, from
February 1998 through July 1999.&#160; From
September 1996 through February 1998, Mr. Biggerstaff provided transportation
consulting services and prior to September 1996, he held various positions,
including regional vice president and general manager, with Ryder Systems,
Inc., a company providing transportation and supply-chain management solutions.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Gary W. Qualmann has served
AirNet as the Chief Financial Officer, Treasurer and Secretary since September
1, 2003.&#160; Prior to joining AirNet, Mr.
Qualmann served as chief financial officer and treasurer of Metatec,Inc., a
manufacturer and distributor of electronic media which filed a voluntary
petition for reorganization under Chapter 11 of the United States Bankruptcy
Code on October 17, 2003, from February 2002 through August 2003</font>. Mr. Qualmann
provided financial consulting services to the Metatec from October, 2001
through February 2002. From March 1996 until June 2001, Mr. Qualmann was chief
financial officer, treasurer, secretary and director of MindLeaders.com, Inc.,
an e-learning company based in Columbus, Ohio. From May 1988 until July 1995,
Mr. Qualmann served as executive vice president and chief financial officer of
Red Roof Inns, Inc., a lodging company based in Hilliard, Ohio.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Larry M. Glasscock, Jr. joined AirNet as
Senior Vice President - Express Services in February, 2003.&#160; From February 2002 through February 2003,
Mr. Glasscock served as senior vice president of Evercom Systems, Inc. a
national provider of telecom services.&#160;
From April 2001 through February 2002, Mr. Glasscock served as executive
vice president of NextJet Technologies, a software and technology solutions
organization.&#160; Mr. Glasscock served as
chief executive officer of Expedited Delivery Systems, Inc., a time-definite
trucking concern from August 1999 to September 2000 and as its president and
chief operating officer from January 1998 through August 1999.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Jeffery B. Harris has served
AirNet as Senior Vice President, Bank Services since May 2000.&#160; Mr. Harris joined AirNet in June 1996 as the
relationship manager for Banking Sales and was appointed vice president, Sales
in the banking division in October 1997.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Craig A. Leach has served as
Vice President, Information Systems since January 2000.&#160; Mr. Leach established AirNet&#146;s Information
Systems Department in 1985 and was named director of Information Systems in
1996.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Stephen K. Lister was appointed
Vice President, Aviation services January 2004.&#160; Prior to that Mr. Lister was vice president, Airline Operations
since February 2001.&#160; Mr. Lister has
served AirNet in a variety of capacities since 1982.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Wynn D. Peterson
currently serves as Vice President, Strategic Planning and Analysis.&#160; Mr. Peterson has served as an officer of the
company since February, 2000 when he was named Vice President of Corporate
Development.&#160; Mr. Peterson joined AirNet
in 1997 as manager of Corporate Development.&#160;
Prior to joining AirNet, Mr. Peterson managed equity and fixed income
portfolios from 1993 until 1997 at Desert Mutual in Salt Lake City, Utah.&#160; From 1988 until 1993, Mr. Peterson held
various management positions in Finance, Corporate Development and Strategic
Planning at AMR Corporation, the parent company of American Airlines, Inc., in
Dallas, Texas.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Michael J. Snyder has served as
Vice President of Airline Operations since February 2004.&#160; Prior to joining AirNet, Mr. Snyder
consulted on various aviation and logistics projects since November 2001.&#160; From May through November 2001 he served as
president and chief executive officer of Polar Air Cargo, a global express air
freight company.&#160; From June 2000 through
May 2001, Mr. Snyder was president and chief executive officer of TrafficStation,
a leading traffic technology service.&#160; </font>From June 1999 through May 2000, Mr. Snyder
served as senior vice president of Operations and Marketing at Smartship and
from April 1998 though November 1999 served as president of the Western and
Midwestern regions of </p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">9</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Corporate Express Delivery Systems.&#160; From October 1996 though April 1998, Mr.
Snyder served as a vice president at FedEx Corporation, where he had also held
various other position with increasing responsibility since 1981.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Kendall W. Wright has served as

He served as Vice President, Sales from 1988 through 2000.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><a name="PartIi"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">PART II</font></b></a></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item5MarketForRegistrantsCommon"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM 5 - MARKET FOR REGISTRANT&#146;S COMMON
EQUITY</font></b></a><b><font style="font-weight:bold;">, AND RELATED STOCKHOLDER MATTERS AND ISSUER PURCHASES
OF EQUITY SECURITIES</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The common shares of AirNet
Systems, Inc. trade on the New York Stock Exchange under the symbol &#147;ANS&#148;.&#160; The table below sets forth the high and low
sales prices of the common shares reported for the periods indicated.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet has not paid any
dividends on its common shares and does not intend to pay any dividends in the
foreseeable future.&#160; AirNet anticipates
using future earnings to finance operations and future growth and development.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
payment of any future dividends on common shares will be determined by the
AirNet Board of Directors in light of conditions then existing, including
earnings, financial condition and capital requirements, restrictions in
financing agreements, business conditions and other factors.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On March 29, 2004, there were
approximately 2,000 holders of AirNet common shares, based upon the number of
holders of record and the number of individual participants in certain security
position listings.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet did not purchase any
common shares during the fourth quarter of the fiscal year.&#160; On February 18, 2000, AirNet announced a
stock repurchase plan under which up to $3.0 million of AirNet common shares
may be repurchased from time to time.&#160;
These repurchases may be made in open market transactions or through
privately negotiated transactions.&#160; As
of December 31, 2003, AirNet had the authority to still repurchase
approximately $0.6 million of AirNet common shares under this stock repurchase
plan.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">10</font></p>


<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.5in;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Note 1</font></b><b><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font></b>2001 includes a
$1.0 million non-recurring charge related to the retirement agreement of Gerald
G. Mercer (see Note 6 to the Consolidated Financial Statements included in Item
8 of this Annual Report on Form 10-K.)</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.5in;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Note 2</font></b><b><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font></b>Represents 2001
non-recurring charge related to the impairment of Float Control, Inc.&#146;s
investment in The Check Exchange System Co. partnership (see Note 1 of the
Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements included in Item 8 of this
Annual Report on Form 10-K.)</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.5in;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Note 3</font></b><b><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font></b>In August 2003,
AirNet sold the assets of its Mercury Business Services unit, resulting in
discontinued operations.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.5in;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Note 4</font></b><b><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font></b>See Notes 1 and 2
of the Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements included in Item 8 for
discussion of the 2002 charge related to the impairment of goodwill in accordance
with the adoption of SFAS No. 142.&#160; In
1998, the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants issued Statement
of Position (SOP)&#160; No. 98-5, Reporting
on the Costs of Start-Up Activities, which requires that costs related to
start-up activities be expensed as incurred.&#160;
Prior to July 1, 1998, AirNet Systems, Inc. capitalized start-up costs
associated with its premium products line of business.&#160; Effective July 1, 1998, AirNet ceased
capitalizing such costs and began amortizing the previously capitalized costs
over five years.&#160; The Company adopted
the provisions of the SOP in its consolidated financial statements as of
January 1, 1999 which resulted in the write-off of unamortized start-up costs
at that time.</p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">11</font></p>


<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='11',FILE='C:\jms\jgronse\04-3778-1\task103431\3778-1-ba.htm',USER='jgronse',CD='Mar 30 09:05 2004' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">
</font>

<p align="center" style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;">&nbsp;</p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item7ManagementsDiscussionAndAna"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM 7 - MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
OF </font></b></a><b><font style="font-weight:bold;">FINANCIAL CONDITION AND RESULTS OF OPERATION</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">General</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s Bank revenues continue
to decline as a result of the continuing evolution of electronic alternatives
to the physical movement of cancelled checks and other market forces.&#160;&#160; The decline in Bank services requires that
AirNet restructure its existing transportation network which was originally
established to service its bank customers.&#160;
AirNet is taking steps to expand its Express and Passenger Charter
services businesses to offset the expected decline in Bank services
revenue.&#160; In addition, AirNet is
evaluating and adjusting its aircraft mix and fleet size in response to these
changing business conditions.&#160; AirNet
introduced the Caravan and eliminated the Aerostar from its fleet in recent
years and, barring new route requirements, intends to eliminate additional
piston aircraft and its Learjet 25&#146;s in 2004.&#160;
AirNet is reviewing its ground operations for efficiencies and cost
reductions and will continue this review throughout 2004.&#160; The security surcharge and modified fuel
surcharge will continue in 2004.&#160;
Changes in AirNet&#146;s regional sales and operational structure, increased
marketing efforts and adaptation of its fleet to changing market conditions are
all critical to achieving AirNet&#146;s goals.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The following management&#146;s
discussion and analysis describes the principal factors affecting the results
of operations, liquidity and capital resources, as well as the critical
accounting policies of AirNet. This discussion should be read in conjunction
with the accompanying audited financial statements, which include additional
information about AirNet&#146;s significant accounting policies, practices and the
transactions that underlie its financial results.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Results of Operations</font></b></p>

Revenues</font></i></b></p>

  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="9%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:9.0%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">5</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.72%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">%</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet has experienced overall net revenue
growth each of the last three years.&#160;
This can be attributed to several factors including increased Express
shipment volume, growth in Passenger Charter services, the implementation of a
security surcharge program in August 2002 and, increased revenues from the fuel
surcharge program resulting from increased fuel prices and changes to the
surcharge program implemented in 2002.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet assesses its customers a fuel surcharge
which is based on the Oil Price Index Summary &#150; Columbus, Ohio (OPIS-CMH
index).&#160; As index rates increase above a
set threshold, surcharge rates increase.&#160;
In August 2002, AirNet modified its fuel surcharge program for its bank
customers to help offset timing differences between market prices and the
OPIS-CHM index used to determine surcharge rates.&#160; In 2001 and through January 2002, AirNet&#146;s Express customers paid
a 4% temporary fuel surcharge on most revenues under a separate program.&#160; In February 2002, AirNet rescinded this 4%
temporary surcharge on Express services revenues and implemented the program
described above based on the OPIS &#150; CMH index.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">12</font></p>


<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(4,090</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in .7pt 0in;width:2.02%;">

  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">-4</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.58%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">%</font></p>
  </td>

</table>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Consistent with AirNet&#146;s expectations, Bank
revenues (excluding the impact of fuel surcharge and federal excise taxes)
continue to decline year over year.&#160;
This decline slowed as AirNet continues to focus on additional services
for banks beyond cancelled check transportation, such as proof of deposit and
interoffice mail delivery services.&#160;
From 2002 to 2003 weekday shipment volume decreased 1.3% per flying day
and weekend shipment volume per flying day was down by 9.8%.&#160; The decrease in weekly shipment volume was
offset by increased fuel surcharges in 2003 as compared to 2002.&#160; Lower check delivery volume as a result of
historically low interest rates and the declining use of checks, contributed to
the reduction in revenues, as did increased competitive factors from regional
carriers and transportation cost reduction initiatives by AirNet&#146;s Bank
customers.&#160; AirNet believes that this
decline will continue as the Check 21 Act becomes effective in October 2004;
however, at this time AirNet is unable to predict the ultimate impact of this
Act on future years.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:45.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Weekday shipment volume decreased 4.8% from
2001 to 2002.&#160; A portion of the relative
lost volume was attributed to additional volume in 2001 that was transported
during the days immediately following the September 11, 2001 tragedy, during
which AirNet transported checks for several of its bank customers who relied on
AirNet for services their normal or secondary vendors could not provide at the
time.&#160; The decrease in weekday volume
was partially offset by a 17.0% increase in weekend shipment volume, rate
increases implemented in January 2002 averaging approximately 2.2% and the
implementation of the security surcharge program related to Bank customers in
September 2002.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

  </td>
  <td width="0%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#cceeff" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:.7%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">%</font></p>
